---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Slashtalk — we built a presence dock for our remote team. Here's why.">
	<main class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6 py-16 sm:py-24">
		<header class="mb-16 flex items-center justify-between gap-3">
			<div class="flex items-center gap-3">
				<img
					src="/favicon.svg"
					alt="Slashtalk"
					width="36"
					height="36"
					class="rounded-lg"
				/>
				<span
					class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900"
					>Slashtalk</span
				>
			</div>
			<nav>
				<a
					href="#install"
					class="text-sm font-medium text-neutral-600 transition hover:text-neutral-900"
					>Install</a
				>
			</nav>
		</header>

		<article class="space-y-7 text-[17px] leading-[1.7] text-neutral-700">
			<h1
				class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 sm:text-4xl"
			>
				We built a presence dock for our remote team. Here's why.
			</h1>

			<p>
				Our team had a coordination problem we kept trying to solve with
				more talking.
			</p>

			<p>
				We're small, fully remote, and we ship fast. Because we aren't 100%
				relying on tickets, we pinged each other constantly — <em
					class="italic text-neutral-900">"hey, are you on this?"</em
				>. We did daily
				standups, status threads, Slack channels. People wouldn't pay
				attention and the noise became louder, not clearer.
			</p>

			<p>
				The tools we'd inherited were built for the old way of work.
				Standups assume your whole day of work fits into two sentences. Ticket tracking assumes people should only work on what they're assigned. Slack channel updates assume people read them. None of
				those assumptions hold at the speed small teams are moving today.
			</p>

			<p>So we built the thing we wished we had.</p>

			<hr class="my-12 border-neutral-200" />

			<p>
				Slashtalk is a floating dock that sits on top of your desktop.
			</p>

			<figure class="my-10">
				<img
					src="/screenshot-dock.png"
					alt="The Slashtalk dock — a row of teammate avatars floating above your other apps."
					class="w-full rounded-xl"
				/>
			</figure>

			<p>
				Each teammate is a card which shows what they're shipping: recent
				PRs, active sessions. The question "what
				are you working on?" stops getting asked because the answer is
				always on your dock.
			</p>

			<figure class="my-10 flex justify-center">
				<img
					src="/screenshot-card.png"
					alt="A teammate card showing recent sessions, current branch, and token usage."
					class="w-full max-w-sm rounded-xl"
				/>
			</figure>

			<p>
				PMs or CEOs constantly pinging developers? They can just go ask. The answers come from
				real code, not a guess.
			</p>

			<figure class="my-10">
				<img
					src="/screenshot-ask.png"
					alt="The Ask window — a chat interface synthesizing what the team shipped this week."
					class="w-full rounded-xl"
				/>
			</figure>

			<p>
				When two of us start editing files that are about to collide,
				both our cards flag it. We catch conflicts in the five minutes
				they're being created.
			</p>

			<p>
				And we purposely left chat or messaging out of this product. We all have enough of those apps on our computers.
			</p>

			<p id="install" class="scroll-mt-8">
				If you'd like to give it a try, install it with your team:
			</p>

			<div class="relative">
				<pre
					class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5 pr-20 text-sm leading-relaxed text-neutral-800"><code id="install-code">git clone https://github.com/HereNotThere/slashtalk.git
cd slashtalk
bun install
bun run start</code></pre>
				<button
					type="button"
					data-copy-target="install-code"
					class="absolute top-3 right-3 inline-flex items-center rounded-md border border-neutral-200 bg-white px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-neutral-700 transition hover:bg-neutral-100"
					aria-label="Copy install commands"
				>
					<span data-copy-label>Copy</span>
				</button>
			</div>


			<p>
				On first launch you'll be asked to authenticate with your git
				provider and point it to your local repo. That's the
				setup.
			</p>
			<p>
				We've been on it ourselves for a while now, and so far, we're shipping more with fewer interruptions and it's been delightful to feel like you're working alongside your teammates even when you're not physically together.
			</p>

			<p>
				If you're on a small team shipping fast with AI and the
				coordination is starting to fray — try it and let us know what
				you think.
			</p>
		</article>

		<footer class="mt-24 border-t border-neutral-200 pt-8 text-sm text-neutral-500">
			Slashtalk — from <a
				href="https://x.com/TownsLabs"
				class="text-neutral-700 underline decoration-neutral-300 underline-offset-4 transition hover:decoration-neutral-700"
				>Towns Labs</a
			>
		</footer>
	</main>
</Layout>

<script>
	const RESET_LABEL = 'Copy';
	const resetTimers = new WeakMap<HTMLElement, number>();

	function flashLabel(label: HTMLSpanElement, text: string) {
		const existing = resetTimers.get(label);
		if (existing !== undefined) clearTimeout(existing);
		label.textContent = text;
		const id = window.setTimeout(() => {
			label.textContent = RESET_LABEL;
			resetTimers.delete(label);
		}, 1500);
		resetTimers.set(label, id);
	}

	document.querySelectorAll<HTMLButtonElement>('[data-copy-target]').forEach(
		(button) => {
			button.addEventListener('click', async () => {
				const targetId = button.getAttribute('data-copy-target');
				if (!targetId) return;
				const target = document.getElementById(targetId);
				if (!target) return;
				const label = button.querySelector<HTMLSpanElement>(
					'[data-copy-label]',
				);
				try {
					await navigator.clipboard.writeText(target.innerText);
					if (label) flashLabel(label, 'Copied');
				} catch {
					if (label) flashLabel(label, 'Failed');
				}
			});
		},
	);
</script>
